disease quite rapidly. And that's despite the fact that everyone's getting the same

510
00:30:07.522 --> 00:30:10.802
type of treatment. So we know that there's heterogeneity in responses within a

511
00:30:10.842 --> 00:30:14.102
cancer. But what I'd like to talk to you a little bit about today is the

512
00:30:14.222 --> 00:30:18.172
differences or the heterogeneity in responses across cancers,

513
00:30:18.222 --> 00:30:22.042
which I think is a really critical question that's not really studied as we silo

514
00:30:22.082 --> 00:30:25.442
all these different cancer types in different sessions, even here at AACR.

515
00:30:26.102 --> 00:30:29.442
So what I'm showing you here is actually a range of different Kaplan-Meier curves

516
00:30:29.482 --> 00:30:31.772
for several different malignancies.

517
00:30:31.782 --> 00:30:35.422
And first, I'll highlight several that are quite responsive to

518
00:30:35.442 --> 00:30:37.661
therapy. So here we see T-ALL,

519
00:30:38.462 --> 00:30:39.382
lymphoblastic leukemia,

520
00:30:40.302 --> 00:30:42.482
diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, follicular lymphoma.

521
00:30:42.862 --> 00:30:46.612
These are cancer types that are largely curable with the existing

522
00:30:46.622 --> 00:30:50.602
regimens that we have today, many of which are going to target the same

523
00:30:50.642 --> 00:30:54.422
types of cellular components that we're targeting in solid

524
00:30:54.442 --> 00:30:58.042
tumors as well. One exception to the incurability or the

525
00:30:58.082 --> 00:31:02.062
difficulty in treating of solid cancers is actually testicular

526
00:31:02.102 --> 00:31:05.642
cancer. Germ cell tumors are profoundly sensitive to cisplatin.

527
00:31:05.682 --> 00:31:09.672
With one therapy, you can actually cure a majority of these patients.

528
00:31:10.492 --> 00:31:13.622
So these are very chemo-sensitive cancer types.

529
00:31:13.642 --> 00:31:17.032
But then we know that there are many other types of cancers that, despite the fact

530
00:31:17.032 --> 00:31:20.642
that we have the same drugs available, respond quite unfavorably to

531
00:31:20.662 --> 00:31:23.872
therapies. Those include things such as sarcomas, hepatocellular carcinoma,

532
00:31:23.982 --> 00:31:26.882
melanoma, and the high-grade serous ovarian cancer that I showed you on the

533
00:31:26.902 --> 00:31:30.732
previous slide. And then we know that there's many

534
00:31:30.762 --> 00:31:33.782
solid cancers, especially, that are profoundly resistant to therapy.

535
00:31:33.842 --> 00:31:36.682
So that includes diseases such as pancreatic cancer, GBMs.

536
00:31:37.182 --> 00:31:40.802
And we wanted to know what is potentially driving some of these major

537
00:31:40.842 --> 00:31:43.242
differences in therapy responses between cancers.

538
00:31:44.082 --> 00:31:47.362
So in the literature, and people would

539
00:31:47.962 --> 00:31:51.932
give you several different types of answers to this question, one of which being,

540
00:31:52.042 --> 00:31:55.672
well, we have different therapies for these different cancers, and that is largely

541
00:31:55.672 --> 00:31:59.322
driving these differences. But if we just rank these cancers that I showed you on

542
00:31:59.342 --> 00:32:02.802
the previous slide according to their outcomes and look at the therapies that we

543
00:32:02.922 --> 00:32:06.402
use for their treatment, we actually see that we're targeting the same exact

544
00:32:06.442 --> 00:32:09.702
cellular components. We're targeting DNA, we're targeting microtubules,

545
00:32:09.782 --> 00:32:13.622
topoisomerases, and yet we can cure 90-plus percent of germ

546
00:32:13.702 --> 00:32:16.982
cell tumors and 0% of GBMs. So clearly,

547
00:32:17.042 --> 00:32:20.992
the applicability of the different therapy answer is

548
00:32:21.102 --> 00:32:23.082
not quite sufficient to answer this.

549
00:32:24.742 --> 00:32:27.982
And I also would like to point out that there's several different types of

550
00:32:28.002 --> 00:32:31.382
therapies that we use largely in solid tumors that are actually

551
00:32:31.822 --> 00:32:35.422
also going to be targeting the same thing in hematologic malignancies and

552
00:32:35.442 --> 00:32:39.152
potentially are going to be even more active there, and I'll show you that in just

553
00:32:39.262 --> 00:32:43.002
a couple seconds. So another potential

554
00:32:43.012 --> 00:32:45.471
answer that's found in the literature is proliferation rates.

555
00:32:45.542 --> 00:32:48.751
People say that the cycling rates of cancers is what really drives their

556
00:32:48.762 --> 00:32:52.742
sensitivity. But if you actually dig a little bit deeper into some of the

557
00:32:52.822 --> 00:32:56.702
actual studies of Ki-67 indexes and things like that, and look at

558
00:32:56.822 --> 00:32:58.742
actual patient responses, you see that

559
00:32:58.982 --> 00:33:02.932
explanation breaks down. And here's another good example of

560
00:33:02.982 --> 00:33:06.802
that across the TCGA. If you just look at proliferating cell nuclear

561
00:33:06.882 --> 00:33:10.602
antigen, mRNA levels, and you look at sensitivity to

562
00:33:10.642 --> 00:33:14.322
therapy, again, here, judging by outcomes or based on

563
00:33:14.362 --> 00:33:18.342
outcomes, you see that's a pretty poor indicator of response to therapy.

564
00:33:19.262 --> 00:33:23.251
So if proliferation rates or different types of therapies aren't good

565
00:33:23.302 --> 00:33:27.122
enough to explain why there's this difference between solid and liquid cancers,

566
00:33:27.422 --> 00:33:29.522
then really what could be the explanation?

567
00:33:30.102 --> 00:33:33.742
Well, we think that the wiring of the cell death pathways in these

568
00:33:33.782 --> 00:33:35.562
cells is a major

569
00:33:37.582 --> 00:33:40.122
contributor to these differences in responses.

570
00:33:40.162 --> 00:33:40.782
And so we

571
00:33:41.642 --> 00:33:45.542
are in particular interested in studying how apoptosis or programmed cell death

572
00:33:45.582 --> 00:33:48.922
is regulated in cancers and may contribute to different responses.

573
00:33:48.962 --> 00:33:51.922
So apoptosis is very important for sculpting our tissues, important

574
00:33:52.001 --> 00:33:55.802
developmentally, and also is critical to understand that

575
00:33:55.822 --> 00:33:59.422
most cancer therapies have used both cytotoxic as well as targeted agents,

576
00:34:00.282 --> 00:34:04.132
as well as ionizing radiation produce pro-apoptotic signaling in cancer

577
00:34:04.182 --> 00:34:07.832
cells. Don't always kill via apoptosis, but certainly produce that kind of

578
00:34:07.942 --> 00:34:08.303
stress.

579
00:34:09.562 --> 00:34:11.292
So how does this pathway actually wired?

580
00:34:11.502 --> 00:34:14.022
So it's controlled by the BCL2 family of proteins.

581
00:34:14.473 --> 00:34:18.332
These are going to be mobilized in response to a range of different death and

582
00:34:18.422 --> 00:34:22.162
stress stimuli. Usually, there's some type of upstream signaling that is

583
00:34:22.203 --> 00:34:26.022
first activated. P53 is a good example, ER stress response,

584
00:34:26.102 --> 00:34:29.522
kinase inhibition. This leads to the production of proapoptotic

585
00:34:29.723 --> 00:34:33.602
activator proteins such as Bim, Bid, and Puma, that can do one of two

586
00:34:33.622 --> 00:34:36.822
things. One is that they can translocate to the mitochondria, where they can be

587
00:34:36.862 --> 00:34:40.382
bound and sequestered by pro-survival proteins, BCL2, BCL-XL,

588
00:34:40.522 --> 00:34:41.162
Mcl1.

589
00:34:42.283 --> 00:34:45.962
If these are sequestered, the cell can stay alive and is not able to be

590
00:34:46.263 --> 00:34:49.942
evident that there's any kind of morphological change or any biochemical change

591
00:34:50.022 --> 00:34:50.203
even.

592
00:34:51.322 --> 00:34:54.582
However, once we overwhelm these pro-survival proteins, something a little bit

593
00:34:54.622 --> 00:34:58.342
different happens, which is that the Bim and Bid molecules can actually bind to Bax

594
00:34:58.362 --> 00:35:01.922
and Bak, the pore-forming proapoptotic proteins, and cause the

595
00:35:01.942 --> 00:35:04.602
permeabilization of the mitochondrial outer membrane.

596
00:35:04.662 --> 00:35:08.282
Once this happens, cytochrome C is released into the cytoplasm, where it binds to

597
00:35:08.322 --> 00:35:12.142
Apaf-1 and activates caspases. Now, caspases are the

598
00:35:12.202 --> 00:35:16.142
executioners of apoptotic cell death and actually prepare the cell for phagocytic

599
00:35:16.202 --> 00:35:20.172
clearance. So based on the BCL2 family protein interactions,

600
00:35:20.342 --> 00:35:23.382
we can already start to imagine that the different states at the level of the

601
00:35:23.391 --> 00:35:26.302
mitochondria may lead to different cell fates.

602
00:35:26.342 --> 00:35:29.132
So here I'm showing you a cell that has pro-survival proteins, but they're already

603
00:35:29.222 --> 00:35:31.002
sequestering pro-death signals.

604
00:35:31.042 --> 00:35:34.782
We refer to this cell as being primed for apoptosis because when this cell is now

605
00:35:34.842 --> 00:35:38.582
challenged with chemotherapy treatment, it's very easy to now trigger

606
00:35:38.622 --> 00:35:41.782
Bax and Bak activation and the release of cytochrome C in the rest of the

607
00:35:41.842 --> 00:35:45.792
cascade.In this other cell, however, we see that there are some

608
00:35:45.812 --> 00:35:49.612
pro-survival proteins unbound. In this case, when we first challenge the

609
00:35:49.652 --> 00:35:50.801
cell with some type of therapy,

610
00:35:51.672 --> 00:35:55.452
those initial apoptotic signals can be sequestered, the cell stays

611
00:35:55.492 --> 00:35:59.292
alive. It takes additional treatment to actually be able to trigger cell

612
00:35:59.312 --> 00:36:01.972
death in the cell. We refer to this as being unprimed.

613
00:36:03.852 --> 00:36:07.832
Finally, we have a separate type of scenario here, where we're actually

614
00:36:07.852 --> 00:36:09.892
missing the pore-forming proteins entirely.

615
00:36:10.282 --> 00:36:14.172
It doesn't matter how much proapoptotic signaling we produce in these cells

616
00:36:14.192 --> 00:36:18.152
with the existing therapies, we will never trigger apoptotic cell death because Bax

617
00:36:18.172 --> 00:36:20.652
and Bak are missing. I'll give you a sigh of relief.

618
00:36:21.272 --> 00:36:24.552
It's a vast minority of cancers that actually have this apoptosis

619
00:36:24.572 --> 00:36:28.472
refractory state. Most cancers are actually going to be in that primed or unprimed

620
00:36:28.512 --> 00:36:31.922
category. However, many of our healthy tissues are exactly this way, and that's

621
00:36:31.922 --> 00:36:34.172
what protects them from a lot of chemotherapeutic treatments.

622
00:36:35.562 --> 00:36:39.361
So based on this understanding, we can already start to think, well, if we can

623
00:36:39.392 --> 00:36:42.962
understand the state of the cell before therapy is administered,

624
00:36:43.272 --> 00:36:46.632
perhaps that will give us some clues as to how the cancers are going to respond.

625
00:36:47.132 --> 00:36:50.832
So Tony Letai, the current NCI director, actually developed this really neat assay

626
00:36:50.892 --> 00:36:53.612
called BH3 profiling that measures apoptotic priming.

627
00:36:53.802 --> 00:36:57.152
And I don't have the time to go into it in detail, but it's basically,

628
00:36:57.672 --> 00:37:01.472
the idea is to titrate in doses of proapoptotic signals, BH3

629
00:37:01.592 --> 00:37:05.451
peptides, that mimic the activity of the full-length BH3-only proteins.

630
00:37:05.752 --> 00:37:09.512
In this case, we're titrating in the BIM peptide, which can bind

631
00:37:09.552 --> 00:37:13.392
and inactivate the pro-survival proteins, but then activate Bax and Bak.

632
00:37:13.872 --> 00:37:17.152
And then we can use a very simple readout of cytochrome C release to know whether

633
00:37:17.232 --> 00:37:21.032
that cell has undergone that mitochondrial permeabilization or not using antibody

634
00:37:21.052 --> 00:37:21.452
staining.

635
00:37:22.272 --> 00:37:26.192
So then we can run this on flow cytometry and look at the populations of cells

636
00:37:26.212 --> 00:37:30.172
that actually release cytochrome C versus those that do not, and we can score them

637
00:37:30.352 --> 00:37:32.882
and give them a priming designation.

638
00:37:33.552 --> 00:37:37.492
So we set out a long time ago to first check whether apoptotic priming actually

639
00:37:37.612 --> 00:37:40.832
affects whether patients respond well to cancer therapies.

640
00:37:41.432 --> 00:37:45.212
And so we used this in ovarian cancer to first look at whether there

641
00:37:45.332 --> 00:37:48.142
are differences in priming. We saw indeed that there were differences.

642
00:37:48.532 --> 00:37:51.992
Some ovarian primary tumors were highly primed for apoptosis, while others were

643
00:37:52.012 --> 00:37:55.862
fairly resistant. When we looked at patient outcomes, we saw that those that

644
00:37:55.952 --> 00:37:58.992
had more primed cancers had faster normalization of

645
00:37:59.012 --> 00:38:02.812
CA125, indicating a faster clinical response,

646
00:38:03.332 --> 00:38:05.292
also had improved progression-free survival.

647
00:38:05.872 --> 00:38:09.122
Now, colleagues in Letai lab have also found that this was the case in chronic

648
00:38:09.152 --> 00:38:10.812
lymphocytic leukemia and AML.

649
00:38:11.672 --> 00:38:14.622
However, this is not what I set out to talk about today.

650
00:38:15.002 --> 00:38:18.252
I really wanted to get at this question of what about across different cancer

651
00:38:18.332 --> 00:38:21.872
types? What can we learn from the same type of assay and the same type of

652
00:38:22.912 --> 00:38:25.872
analyses about the differences between cancers?

653
00:38:26.792 --> 00:38:30.612
Well, one thing that we wanted to know first is wanted to know whether different

654
00:38:30.672 --> 00:38:34.272
cancer cell lines reflect the sensitivity of the

655
00:38:34.332 --> 00:38:37.252
cancers that they come from to therapies.

656
00:38:37.612 --> 00:38:40.792
So here I'm showing you a range of different cancer cell lines from the DepMap

657
00:38:41.592 --> 00:38:44.652
database and showing their sensitivity to cisplatin.

658
00:38:45.092 --> 00:38:49.052
And these are just scored according to their IC50s, with

659
00:38:49.072 --> 00:38:50.932
the ones on the left side being more sensitive.

660
00:38:51.422 --> 00:38:55.372
And what becomes very clear very quickly is that blood cancers

661
00:38:55.412 --> 00:38:58.712
such as lymphocytic leukemias, B cell leukemias,

662
00:38:59.452 --> 00:39:03.352
other lymphoid neoplasms, are more sensitive to even

663
00:39:03.392 --> 00:39:07.351
cisplatin, which is a drug typically used for solid tumors, than the

664
00:39:07.392 --> 00:39:10.932
solid cancers on the right side that this drug is actually used for more

665
00:39:10.972 --> 00:39:11.432
commonly.

666
00:39:12.672 --> 00:39:16.552
If we take a step back and look at all DNA-damaging agents and score their

667
00:39:16.572 --> 00:39:20.541
responses across these cancer cell lines, we see that it largely

668
00:39:20.552 --> 00:39:22.152
reflects a very similar paradigm.

669
00:39:22.912 --> 00:39:26.112
Blood cancers are dramatically more sensitive to these

670
00:39:26.752 --> 00:39:30.652
DNA-damaging agents than solid cancer cell lines, especially ones that are

671
00:39:30.672 --> 00:39:34.452
highly resistant to these treatments in patients.

672
00:39:34.792 --> 00:39:38.532
Some of the clear outliers here are things such as testicular cancer

673
00:39:38.552 --> 00:39:39.232
cells, which

674
00:39:40.232 --> 00:39:44.152
continue to be very sensitive, reflecting their sensitivity in

675
00:39:44.192 --> 00:39:48.032
patients as well. Taking a further step back, what if we look at

676
00:39:48.112 --> 00:39:51.732
all cytotoxic drugs? Again, we see the same trend coming up.

677
00:39:51.972 --> 00:39:55.912
Blood cancers, dramatically more sensitive to these therapies than solid

678
00:39:56.292 --> 00:39:57.032
cancer cell lines.

679
00:39:58.172 --> 00:40:01.082
And in fact, even if you look at all the targeted agents, many of which were

680
00:40:01.152 --> 00:40:05.002
actually developed for solid cancer cells, you still

681
00:40:05.072 --> 00:40:07.062
see that the blood cancers are more sensitive.

682
00:40:07.512 --> 00:40:10.602
So this points to very clearly that there is some kind of

683
00:40:10.632 --> 00:40:14.612
inherent cell-intrinsic sensitivity of blood cancer cells to

684
00:40:14.672 --> 00:40:16.152
a wide range of different therapies.

685
00:40:17.772 --> 00:40:21.552
Now, we wanted to know whether apoptotic priming is capable of giving us a major

686
00:40:21.612 --> 00:40:25.432
difference in therapy outcomes. So we used an isogenic system, HeLa cells.

687
00:40:25.772 --> 00:40:29.612
We knocked out Bax and Bak to blunt the apoptotic sensitivity of these

688
00:40:29.652 --> 00:40:33.352
cells, and then we performed BH3 profiling and a range of chemosensitivity

689
00:40:33.362 --> 00:40:37.142
analyses. When we remove Bax or Bak or both Bax and

690
00:40:37.172 --> 00:40:40.952
Bak, we see that there's a decrease in apoptotic priming in these cells.

691
00:40:40.992 --> 00:40:44.572
We are suppressing the apoptosis pathway, and we can see that based on the BH3

692
00:40:44.632 --> 00:40:48.392
profiling assay. When we challenge these cells with a range of different

693
00:40:48.412 --> 00:40:51.292
chemotherapeutic agents, we see exactly what we would expect to see.

694
00:40:51.512 --> 00:40:54.792
They become dramatically more resistant to a wide range of different

695
00:40:54.812 --> 00:40:56.012
chemotherapeutic agents.

696
00:40:56.852 --> 00:40:59.292
And this is also true if we look at colony formation assays.

697
00:40:59.332 --> 00:41:02.472
These cells are not only able to survive longer, but they're actually able to grow

698
00:41:02.552 --> 00:41:05.272
out and survive and potentially

699
00:41:06.252 --> 00:41:08.672
lead to things such as tumor recurrence in patients.

700
00:41:10.352 --> 00:41:14.272
So when we apply this BH3 profiling technique to a range of cancer

701
00:41:14.332 --> 00:41:18.312
cell lines, we see that there are definitely differences between them.

702
00:41:18.452 --> 00:41:22.432
And when we summarize them by cancer type, we see that this again reflects what we

703
00:41:22.492 --> 00:41:26.472
saw clinically, which is that these blood cancers that are more

704
00:41:26.512 --> 00:41:30.392
sensitive to therapies in the clinic, also the cancer cell lines end up

705
00:41:30.412 --> 00:41:34.282
being more primed for apoptosis. Interestingly, we also see that

706
00:41:34.312 --> 00:41:38.062
pediatric CNS cancers and the cell lines coming from them, such

707
00:41:38.132 --> 00:41:41.972
as medulloblastoma cell lines, also highly primed for apoptosis.

708
00:41:42.392 --> 00:41:46.172
That's also one of the outliers. We know that we can cure about 80% to 90%

709
00:41:46.212 --> 00:41:49.872
of pediatric medulloblastoma patients with existing cytotoxic

710
00:41:49.892 --> 00:41:53.576
chemotherapy and radiation.The most resistant

711
00:41:53.636 --> 00:41:57.396
cancer types on the right side ended up also being more resistant

712
00:41:57.456 --> 00:42:01.176
to these proapoptotic signals And so when we look at the correlation

713
00:42:01.196 --> 00:42:04.296
between the priming and the actual sensitivity to

714
00:42:05.396 --> 00:42:08.635
chemotherapeutic agents, we see that it's pretty well

715
00:42:08.716 --> 00:42:12.496
aligned with at least a third of the differences in

716
00:42:12.556 --> 00:42:16.266
chemotherapy sensitivity potentially being able to be explained by differences in

717
00:42:16.296 --> 00:42:17.176
apoptotic priming.

718
00:42:19.016 --> 00:42:22.796
Now, this is another analysis that we performed on about 150

719
00:42:22.816 --> 00:42:26.436
different cancer cell lines to look at their sensitivity to

720
00:42:26.516 --> 00:42:30.146
agents that directly target the BCL2 family proteins, including

721
00:42:30.656 --> 00:42:33.576
drugs that target BCLXL, BCL2, and MCL1.

722
00:42:33.706 --> 00:42:37.156
Now, I don't expect you to look at the details here, but what I just wanted to

723
00:42:37.196 --> 00:42:40.796
point out is that the only cancer cell lines that actually exhibit

724
00:42:41.176 --> 00:42:44.776
single agent sensitivity to these drugs targeting BCL2 family

725
00:42:44.856 --> 00:42:48.536
proteins are really blood cancers and some pediatric

726
00:42:48.816 --> 00:42:52.716
CNS tumor cell lines, indicating that in most solid cancer cell

727
00:42:52.776 --> 00:42:56.496
lines, you actually have to go and hit at least two or maybe even

728
00:42:56.536 --> 00:43:00.356
three of these pro-survival proteins before you can actually induce cell death.

729
00:43:00.756 --> 00:43:04.256
Again, pointing to this difference between solid and liquid cancers.

730
00:43:06.156 --> 00:43:08.316
We also wanted to test this in primary cancer.

731
00:43:08.436 --> 00:43:12.386
So we collected either primary material from patients directly

732
00:43:12.416 --> 00:43:16.366
in a clinic or from genetically engineered mouse models and compared

733
00:43:16.396 --> 00:43:19.916
the priming in the cancers that we were able to

734
00:43:20.016 --> 00:43:20.416
analyze.

735
00:43:21.676 --> 00:43:23.196
What we found was quite

736
00:43:24.036 --> 00:43:26.836
interesting and reflected what we had seen in the cell lines.

737
00:43:26.876 --> 00:43:30.846
We saw that when we looked at chronic lymphocytic leukemia primary specimens,

738
00:43:30.936 --> 00:43:34.576
follicular lymphoma, AML specimens, they were primed for apoptosis.

739
00:43:34.756 --> 00:43:37.216
Testicular cancer also primed for apoptosis.

740
00:43:37.856 --> 00:43:40.116
Ovarian cancer, interestingly, had a large spread.

741
00:43:40.156 --> 00:43:44.116
There was a lot of heterogeneity to it, and perhaps that's underlying some of the

742
00:43:44.126 --> 00:43:47.246
differences and potential cures that we see in a subset of these.

743
00:43:48.416 --> 00:43:50.536
Breast cancers were less primed than those.

744
00:43:50.556 --> 00:43:54.316
And then as we went out further and further, we saw that some of the cancers that

745
00:43:54.336 --> 00:43:58.116
are least chemosensitive in patients are also those that are

746
00:43:58.176 --> 00:44:01.955
least primed for apoptosis, including pancreatic cancer and adult

747
00:44:02.016 --> 00:44:04.356
rhabdomyosarcoma, hepatocellular carcinoma.

748
00:44:06.216 --> 00:44:08.756
We then set out to, of course, one, it's a study.

749
00:44:08.816 --> 00:44:12.276
Well, what is actually driving the level or what is determining the level of

750
00:44:12.296 --> 00:44:14.116
apoptotic priming in these cancer cells?

751
00:44:14.446 --> 00:44:18.216
And we've examined a range of different things, including metabolic effects,

752
00:44:18.396 --> 00:44:21.416
changes in oncogenes. There's a range of different things that we studied.

753
00:44:21.856 --> 00:44:24.316
I don't have the time to go into each one of those in detail.

754
00:44:24.356 --> 00:44:27.626
I'll just tell you what ended up being the most dominant factor,

755
00:44:27.856 --> 00:44:31.256
which, as I've already sort of alluded to, ends up being the cell of

756
00:44:31.316 --> 00:44:33.536
origin. And we really found that out by

757
00:44:34.436 --> 00:44:36.036
performing tumor genesis studies.

758
00:44:36.096 --> 00:44:39.816
So we looked at the apoptotic priming in the cell of origin or the tissue of origin

759
00:44:39.856 --> 00:44:41.616
versus the cancers that emerged from them.

760
00:44:41.736 --> 00:44:45.716
And in this case, this is the KPC mouse model of pancreatic cancer driven

761
00:44:45.736 --> 00:44:49.156
by KRAS and P53 loss. When we compared the level of

762
00:44:49.236 --> 00:44:52.776
priming in the normal pancreas versus the pan in early

763
00:44:52.786 --> 00:44:56.456
lesions versus the full-blown pancreatic cancer, we saw that there was a

764
00:44:56.516 --> 00:44:58.405
trend toward increased apoptotic priming.

765
00:44:59.216 --> 00:45:03.146
When we looked at the genetic changes that underlie this, transcriptional

766
00:45:03.236 --> 00:45:06.786
changes, we saw that there was a huge upregulation of proapoptotic signaling,

767
00:45:06.896 --> 00:45:08.356
proapoptotic mRNAs

768
00:45:09.736 --> 00:45:13.716
related to expression of Bax and Bak, as well as many of the proapoptotic proteins

769
00:45:13.736 --> 00:45:17.606
that I previously mentioned, indicating that as cells are transforming into a

770
00:45:17.656 --> 00:45:21.536
tumor cell, they are also experiencing apoptotic stress.

771
00:45:22.356 --> 00:45:25.976
This was also the case in the Madd-2 model of hepatocellular carcinoma

772
00:45:26.436 --> 00:45:30.256
and was also the case in high-grade serous ovarian cancer, where we looked at

773
00:45:30.296 --> 00:45:33.856
healthy fallopian tube epithelial cells as well as borderline tumors and then

774
00:45:33.936 --> 00:45:36.456
full-blown high-grade serous ovarian cancers.

775
00:45:38.336 --> 00:45:41.976
So this gave us the clue that potentially the shifts from a

776
00:45:42.016 --> 00:45:45.576
normal cell to a tumor cell was

777
00:45:45.656 --> 00:45:49.356
associated with an increase in priming, but then that starting cell was

778
00:45:49.396 --> 00:45:52.986
potentially a key determinant of where the final tumors ended up.

779
00:45:53.496 --> 00:45:57.476
And so we looked at the healthy cells and the healthy tissues where all the

780
00:45:57.516 --> 00:46:01.296
other cancers had originated from to compare that level of priming.

781
00:46:01.316 --> 00:46:04.936
And so for CLL and follicular lymphoma, they originate from peripheral B cells, and

782
00:46:04.956 --> 00:46:08.476
we saw that those cells are also extremely highly primed for apoptosis.

783
00:46:08.516 --> 00:46:11.116
Hematopoietic stem cells, the precursors for AMLs

784
00:46:12.716 --> 00:46:14.216
also highly primed for apoptosis.

785
00:46:15.096 --> 00:46:18.816
Normal testicular germ cells quite primed and

786
00:46:19.096 --> 00:46:22.876
linked to that level of the priming that we see in testicular cancer.

787
00:46:23.816 --> 00:46:27.236
In the fallopian tube epithelial cells, we see that they are also sensitive to

788
00:46:27.276 --> 00:46:31.176
these apoptotic signals. And again and again, as we went down the line, we see

789
00:46:31.256 --> 00:46:34.936
that the tissues that these cancers are originating

790
00:46:34.996 --> 00:46:38.776
from have differences in their apoptotic priming that then reflect the cancer that

791
00:46:38.856 --> 00:46:39.716
arises from them.

792
00:46:40.536 --> 00:46:43.496
So we can just run a quick correlational analysis and see something quite

793
00:46:43.536 --> 00:46:44.416
interesting popping up,

794
00:46:45.536 --> 00:46:49.276
which is that hematologic malignancies are by far the

795
00:46:49.316 --> 00:46:53.256
most primed cancers that we have studied, and they actually

796
00:46:53.276 --> 00:46:55.856
are just as primed as the precursors they come from.

797
00:46:56.456 --> 00:47:00.256
And so interestingly, we think that their precursors are so highly

798
00:47:00.316 --> 00:47:04.256
primed that they actually need to undergo this evasion of apoptosis that we

799
00:47:04.296 --> 00:47:07.066
know is a hallmark of cancer development.

800
00:47:07.616 --> 00:47:11.226
However, in many other cancer types that originate from solid tumors and

801
00:47:11.256 --> 00:47:15.166
from cells that are extremely resistant to apoptosis at

802
00:47:15.196 --> 00:47:18.556
the starting point, we actually don't think that they have to undergo this evasion

803
00:47:18.576 --> 00:47:21.736
of apoptosis because they actually have a huge buffer built into them.

804
00:47:22.136 --> 00:47:25.756
And so as they get slightly more stressed during this tumor genesis process,

805
00:47:26.136 --> 00:47:29.876
they can still maintain that survival without having to

806
00:47:29.916 --> 00:47:33.892
dysregulate the apoptosis pathway.So

807
00:47:33.932 --> 00:47:36.192
as a final vignette, we wanted to show you

808
00:47:36.212 --> 00:47:39.882
this

809
00:47:39.912 --> 00:47:43.592
interesting idea about, well, if we could change the starting

810
00:47:43.632 --> 00:47:47.392
point of a cancer cell, would it potentially lead to a difference in the

811
00:47:47.412 --> 00:47:49.991
priming and chemosensitivity of the tumor that emerged?

812
00:47:50.362 --> 00:47:52.012
And this was work done with David Kirsch.

813
00:47:52.472 --> 00:47:56.172
He's an expert in pediatric rhabdomyosarcoma, has this really wonderful

814
00:47:56.212 --> 00:47:57.132
model of

815
00:47:58.032 --> 00:48:01.572
inducible rhabdomyosarcoma that we utilize for these studies.

816
00:48:02.132 --> 00:48:05.192
So rhabdomyosarcoma can arise in pediatric as well as

817
00:48:05.252 --> 00:48:09.132
adult individuals, and the actual

818
00:48:09.192 --> 00:48:12.582
outcomes are quite different. In pediatric, in children or adolescents,

819
00:48:12.632 --> 00:48:16.492
they're quite a bit more chemosensitive, and radiation sensitive

820
00:48:16.532 --> 00:48:20.252
than those in adults. So we wanted to model this, and so we

821
00:48:20.292 --> 00:48:24.112
utilized a kind of a trick, which is that we've previously found

822
00:48:24.122 --> 00:48:27.462
that healthy tissues in young individuals are actually more primed for

823
00:48:27.492 --> 00:48:31.222
apoptosis than in adults. That's because as tissues are growing and

824
00:48:31.252 --> 00:48:35.152
remodeling, you actually need to utilize that apoptosis pathway to prune cells

825
00:48:35.412 --> 00:48:38.952
that are superfluous or damaged. And so we

826
00:48:39.352 --> 00:48:43.172
looked in a skeletal muscle of young mice, so this P1 to P5, so

827
00:48:43.212 --> 00:48:46.072
neonatal mice versus adult mice. And we saw that the

828
00:48:47.232 --> 00:48:50.812
muscle satellite cells in the young mice were much more primed for

829
00:48:50.872 --> 00:48:54.792
apoptosis. And so we took advantage of David Kirsch's system

830
00:48:54.852 --> 00:48:58.732
to induce K-RAS activation and knockout of p53

831
00:48:58.792 --> 00:49:02.712
in these muscle satellite cells and drove the development of rhabdomyosarcomas,

832
00:49:02.792 --> 00:49:04.852
either from neonatal or adult mice.

833
00:49:05.812 --> 00:49:09.732
They were essentially identical when it came to histology and other parameters

834
00:49:09.792 --> 00:49:12.392
that were reflecting the actual disease state.

835
00:49:12.412 --> 00:49:15.912
But when we looked at the apoptotic priming in the pediatric versus adult

836
00:49:16.732 --> 00:49:18.772
rhabdomyosarcomas, we saw that they were different.

837
00:49:19.132 --> 00:49:22.872
The pediatric tumors that emerged from the young muscle were more

838
00:49:22.892 --> 00:49:26.332
primed for apoptosis than the adult. And you can see that, here.

839
00:49:27.472 --> 00:49:30.412
So then we wanted to know, well, does that then lead to a difference in the

840
00:49:30.472 --> 00:49:33.232
sensitivity to therapy in this cancer?

841
00:49:33.632 --> 00:49:36.902
And so we, again, induced these tumors,

842
00:49:37.672 --> 00:49:41.092
treated them with the standard of care, which is vincristine for

843
00:49:41.352 --> 00:49:45.321
rhabdomyosarcoma. And we saw that while the adult rhabdomyosarcoma were completely

844
00:49:45.372 --> 00:49:48.932
insensitive to this treatment, the pediatric ones actually had some

845
00:49:48.972 --> 00:49:52.661
response. Wasn't a very satisfying response, but we saw something that

846
00:49:52.972 --> 00:49:56.632
was better than the adult. When we looked at the underlying molecular

847
00:49:56.732 --> 00:50:00.132
biology here to try to understand what's driving these differences in

848
00:50:00.192 --> 00:50:04.112
priming between these two different settings, we saw that

849
00:50:04.172 --> 00:50:08.161
the young muscle actually had higher levels of these pro-apoptotic proteins,

850
00:50:08.692 --> 00:50:11.692
which was then reflected in the tumors that emerged from them.

851
00:50:12.032 --> 00:50:15.792
So the higher Bax levels in the young mice led to that higher level of

852
00:50:15.832 --> 00:50:19.152
priming and was maintained in the cancers that emerged.

853
00:50:19.532 --> 00:50:23.492
We also saw higher levels of pro-apoptotic Bim, and interestingly, also very high

854
00:50:23.592 --> 00:50:27.542
levels of BCL-XL and MCL1, which then led us to hypothesize that

855
00:50:27.552 --> 00:50:29.622
perhaps if we sensitize these tumors

856
00:50:31.652 --> 00:50:35.612
using tools such as BCL-XL inhibitors, we could then improve the

857
00:50:35.672 --> 00:50:38.812
responses to therapy in this model.

858
00:50:39.692 --> 00:50:43.672
And so we did exactly that. We treated these mice with not only vincristine, but

859
00:50:43.712 --> 00:50:47.392
also combined it with a BCL-XL degrader DT2216,

860
00:50:47.792 --> 00:50:50.892
and we saw that they actually responded much more favorably, which

861
00:50:51.432 --> 00:50:55.212
indicates to us that BH3 mimetics are

862
00:50:55.292 --> 00:50:58.752
one method that we can use to sensitize some of these very

863
00:50:58.832 --> 00:51:02.632
unprimed cancers, and actually get an improvement in

864
00:51:02.652 --> 00:51:03.982
responses in patients.

865
00:51:05.082 --> 00:51:08.302
So that just brings us to the kind of the conclusions in the model that we have

866
00:51:08.352 --> 00:51:12.292
here. I didn't go into the Myc versus RAS differences, but we see oncogenes

867
00:51:12.332 --> 00:51:16.062
being able to modulate this property in cells during transformation.

868
00:51:16.492 --> 00:51:20.221
But really the idea that we were left with is that

869
00:51:20.572 --> 00:51:21.852
the cancer cells that emerge

870
00:51:22.772 --> 00:51:26.712
are largely dependent on the apoptosis pathway in

871
00:51:26.752 --> 00:51:30.572
the starting cell. So in this case, an epithelial cell is going to yield a

872
00:51:31.192 --> 00:51:32.132
cancer cell that has a

873
00:51:33.152 --> 00:51:34.912
certain level of priming reflecting that,

874
00:51:36.172 --> 00:51:40.092
and that's driven largely by oncogenes increasing or decreasing that level of

875
00:51:40.132 --> 00:51:43.752
priming. However, cancer cells that come from

876
00:51:43.952 --> 00:51:47.752
very highly primed precursors such as B cells, T cells, or young

877
00:51:47.872 --> 00:51:51.752
tissues such as young muscle or young brain cells, actually are set to

878
00:51:51.812 --> 00:51:53.532
be much more highly primed to start with.

879
00:51:53.972 --> 00:51:57.772
And alternatively, those that come from cells in adult

880
00:51:58.832 --> 00:52:02.212
terminally differentiated tissues that are very apoptosis restricted

881
00:52:02.692 --> 00:52:06.472
end up being very unprimed. And so we think that the future lies,

882
00:52:07.112 --> 00:52:11.052
hopefully in some use of priming agents that can help us increase

883
00:52:11.062 --> 00:52:13.072
the sensitivity of these resistant cancers.

884
00:52:14.072 --> 00:52:18.032
So with that, I'd just like to thank the great individuals that did this work in my

885
00:52:18.052 --> 00:52:21.922
lab, especially Xing Ping and Cam Frazier, who have been fantastic

886
00:52:21.972 --> 00:52:24.152
at doing all the in vitro and in vivo experiments.

887
00:52:24.482 --> 00:52:25.752
And thank you all so much for your attention.

888
00:52:30.912 --> 00:52:33.792
Thank you very much. Questions for Christopher.

889
00:52:34.572 --> 00:52:34.992
Hi, Chris.

890
00:52:35.992 --> 00:52:39.372
Thank you very much for your talk, great data, and of course, very

891
00:52:40.012 --> 00:52:43.782
appealing to think of a priming that is predefined and

892
00:52:43.892 --> 00:52:46.272
can maybe translate even into the cancers.

893
00:52:46.352 --> 00:52:49.272
You group the hematopoietic cancers together,

894
00:52:50.732 --> 00:52:51.172
mostly.

895
00:52:52.142 --> 00:52:52.512
And,

896
00:52:53.372 --> 00:52:57.072
we've just seen that the venetoclax data for the MDSs or the

897
00:52:57.132 --> 00:53:00.892
myelodysplastic syndromes have failed in a third line in

898
00:53:01.152 --> 00:53:04.412
a phase III trial to really make any benefit.

899
00:53:04.972 --> 00:53:08.412
Do you think the availability of the compounds at

900
00:53:09.552 --> 00:53:13.492
the correct site within the cell, is it the right compound that we don't have

901
00:53:13.552 --> 00:53:17.272
yet, or is it the right way of applying them that is missing?

902
00:53:18.092 --> 00:53:21.832
Because when can we really translate this priming into clinical efficacy?

903
00:53:22.816 --> 00:53:26.776
Yeah, it's a great question. And I should mention that I am lumping

904
00:53:26.816 --> 00:53:30.655
together a lot of heme malignancies, and we know that there are some that are very

905
00:53:30.696 --> 00:53:33.736
difficult to control. AML is a great example of that.

906
00:53:34.176 --> 00:53:38.026
A huge tumor burden, very high mutation rate, very aggressive cancer,

907
00:53:38.116 --> 00:53:41.956
so much harder to overcome or target with these therapies.

908
00:53:42.276 --> 00:53:43.296
When it comes to

909
00:53:44.116 --> 00:53:47.856
what are we still missing for some of these heme malignancies and

910
00:53:47.916 --> 00:53:51.776
targeting apoptosis, I think a lot of it is redundancy

911
00:53:51.836 --> 00:53:54.376
between some of these BCL2 family proteins.

912
00:53:55.235 --> 00:53:58.876
And we have a great BCL2 inhibitor that's already clinically

913
00:53:58.916 --> 00:54:02.816
approved for a subset of cancers in AML, in combination also

914
00:54:03.376 --> 00:54:07.296
very effective. But we need more of these same drugs that can

915
00:54:07.356 --> 00:54:11.156
take care of the rapid adaptation that ends up happening in

916
00:54:11.196 --> 00:54:14.136
these cells in order to preclude the development of resistance.

917
00:54:14.436 --> 00:54:17.996
We see that every time we apply a BCL2 inhibitor onto cells, we see an

918
00:54:18.016 --> 00:54:21.816
upregulation of MCL1 and BCL-XL. We need to come up with really

919
00:54:21.896 --> 00:54:22.516
rational,

920
00:54:23.676 --> 00:54:27.376
reasonable ways to be able to target those escape mechanisms

921
00:54:27.696 --> 00:54:30.916
in order to get these durable responses that we're really looking for in such

922
00:54:31.316 --> 00:54:32.236
fast-growing cancers.

923
00:54:34.056 --> 00:54:35.736
Thank you for the really cool talk.

924
00:54:37.116 --> 00:54:40.296
I was wondering if we could speculate

925
00:54:41.436 --> 00:54:44.516
exercise as one of the priming factors.

926
00:54:44.756 --> 00:54:47.276
And I say that because you mentioned

927
00:54:47.576 --> 00:54:49.816
property

928
00:54:51.136 --> 00:54:54.876
in the young muscle tissue, and muscle is related to

929
00:54:55.436 --> 00:54:57.796
being very metabolically active.

930
00:54:59.076 --> 00:55:03.036
More muscle, the processes that need to develop

931
00:55:03.076 --> 00:55:06.916
more muscle would involve a lot of remodeling, therefore injury and

932
00:55:06.996 --> 00:55:10.296
repair and higher apoptosis by

933
00:55:10.816 --> 00:55:14.656
definition. So could one of the priming factors

934
00:55:14.796 --> 00:55:17.496
be, let's say, resistance training?

935
00:55:18.836 --> 00:55:20.316
Wow, that's an interesting question.

936
00:55:21.976 --> 00:55:25.636
I think that with a lot of what we're talking about here with the

937
00:55:25.706 --> 00:55:29.236
priming, has to do more with the precursors.

938
00:55:29.536 --> 00:55:33.516
So if the cells themselves are remodeling as they are in

939
00:55:33.595 --> 00:55:34.716
a young growing

940
00:55:35.656 --> 00:55:39.366
tissue, if that becomes a cancer,

941
00:55:39.756 --> 00:55:43.686
then you have that memory of the starting point in that cell, and it makes it

942
00:55:43.736 --> 00:55:47.576
more treatable. We don't have evidence showing that a

943
00:55:47.636 --> 00:55:51.396
growing muscle is releasing some kind of factors that it then is priming

944
00:55:51.456 --> 00:55:55.256
other cells to undergo apoptosis and potentially would

945
00:55:55.296 --> 00:55:56.916
make them more sensitive to therapy.

946
00:55:57.296 --> 00:56:00.756
That being said, there are some really interesting studies being done out

947
00:56:00.796 --> 00:56:04.516
there doing certain kinds of muscle stimulation to

948
00:56:04.556 --> 00:56:07.556
release exosomes that might speak to

949
00:56:08.416 --> 00:56:11.456
cancer cells in interesting ways and make them more

950
00:56:11.476 --> 00:56:14.996
chemosensitive. I think that there's evidence now that people

951
00:56:15.036 --> 00:56:18.576
that utilize more exercise have better therapy

952
00:56:18.596 --> 00:56:22.496
responses. There's a lot of confounding factors there,

953
00:56:22.556 --> 00:56:26.356
obviously. But that's an interesting idea that might be worth

954
00:56:26.656 --> 00:56:29.756
looking at, especially if you can nail down just exactly what's being released

955
00:56:29.796 --> 00:56:33.756
during exercise, and if you can identify a factor that is driving those

956
00:56:33.776 --> 00:56:35.376
responses, that could be an interesting avenue.

957
00:56:35.766 --> 00:56:37.016
Thank you.

958
00:56:38.356 --> 00:56:38.516
Hi.

959
00:56:39.436 --> 00:56:42.966
That was a great talk. So my question could be a little naive, but

960
00:56:43.136 --> 00:56:46.536
in your study, did you come across any sex-dependent

961
00:56:46.756 --> 00:56:50.096
diversity in the priming for cancer across-

962
00:56:51.056 --> 00:56:53.936
Sorry, you said any sex-based differences in priming?

963
00:56:54.385 --> 00:56:54.385
Yes.

964
00:56:54.856 --> 00:56:57.476
That's a great question.

965
00:56:58.796 --> 00:56:59.866
Honestly, we haven't looked

966
00:57:00.816 --> 00:57:04.526
very deeply at that. We did one study where we looked at the developing

967
00:57:04.556 --> 00:57:08.156
brain and looked for differences between priming in

968
00:57:09.136 --> 00:57:11.636
neural stem cells between male and female mice.

969
00:57:11.936 --> 00:57:15.576
We didn't see much of a difference, which we are actually looking for because we

970
00:57:15.636 --> 00:57:19.576
know that there's differences in radiation toxicity in

971
00:57:19.796 --> 00:57:23.676
pediatric patients that receive radiation therapy, male

972
00:57:23.716 --> 00:57:26.976
versus female. And so we were looking for potential differences there, and we

973
00:57:27.016 --> 00:57:30.986
didn't see anything. So we haven't done it exhaustively, and I

974
00:57:31.016 --> 00:57:33.436
think that it would be an interesting thing to continue looking upon.

975
00:57:33.476 --> 00:57:35.796
But we didn't see it in the studies thus far.

976
00:57:36.356 --> 00:57:36.716
Thank you.

977
00:57:36.956 --> 00:57:37.596
Thanks for your question.

978
00:57:38.296 --> 00:57:41.015
Hey, Chris. Excellent talk. I don't know if you remember me.

979
00:57:41.056 --> 00:57:42.776
I'm with Matt Davids at DFCI.

980
00:57:43.096 --> 00:57:43.566
Oh, yeah. You look familiar.

981
00:57:43.575 --> 00:57:46.496
And as someone who's learning BH3 profiling, I

982
00:57:46.556 --> 00:57:49.216
had two questions based off of your talk.

983
00:57:50.096 --> 00:57:50.106
Sure.

984
00:57:50.156 --> 00:57:53.616
I know you're showing a lot of data comparing heme malignancies and solid cancers.

985
00:57:54.056 --> 00:57:57.716
And I was wondering if you were using microscopy-based or flow-based

986
00:57:57.776 --> 00:58:01.096
assays or a mixture of the two when you were doing the direct

987
00:58:01.156 --> 00:58:03.296
comparisons between those two types of cancers.

988
00:58:03.576 --> 00:58:05.976
Yeah. This is all flow cytometry-based.

989
00:58:06.316 --> 00:58:06.326
Okay.

990
00:58:06.336 --> 00:58:09.616
Yeah, we kept that the same. But yeah, there's ways to do it via microscopy,

991
00:58:09.836 --> 00:58:12.756
plate-based methods. There's a lot of approaches.

992
00:58:13.356 --> 00:58:16.646
And the second question was, you showed a lot of baseline priming, and I was

993
00:58:16.676 --> 00:58:20.296
curious if the dynamic profiles were different amongst solid versus heme cancers.

994
00:58:20.596 --> 00:58:21.756
Oh, yeah. Great question. So

995
00:58:23.176 --> 00:58:27.156
all of this was just based on the baseline sensitivity

996
00:58:27.196 --> 00:58:31.076
of these cells. So we didn't perturb them with anything and look at responses.

997
00:58:31.096 --> 00:58:34.716
But that's another really neat area where Tony has shown that you can

998
00:58:35.376 --> 00:58:39.316
find early evidence of apoptotic signaling and detect it with BH3

999
00:58:39.336 --> 00:58:43.216
profiling assays. So in these studies, I'm really just showing the baseline.

1000
00:58:43.486 --> 00:58:47.036
We have done some of that, and we're really interested in looking at things such as

1001
00:58:47.096 --> 00:58:50.836
radiation therapy, how that's altering the priming of the

1002
00:58:50.856 --> 00:58:54.516
cells. And sometimes you see very obvious changes where you're seeing an

1003
00:58:54.556 --> 00:58:57.156
upregulation of apoptotic signaling, increased priming.

1004
00:58:57.436 --> 00:59:01.296
But sometimes you actually see suppression, and the dynamics of that

1005
00:59:01.336 --> 00:59:04.736
are really interesting to us, and we want to try to understand that in order to

1006
00:59:05.036 --> 00:59:08.536
more rationally combine agents for effective therapeutics.

1007
00:59:08.916 --> 00:59:09.436
So yeah.

1008
00:59:10.536 --> 00:59:11.876
Be happy to chat more about that.

1009
00:59:11.936 --> 00:59:12.196
Great.

1010
00:59:12.296 --> 00:59:13.216
Thank you very much.

1011
00:59:14.456 --> 00:59:18.096
So we'll listen now to the last talk

1012
00:59:18.196 --> 00:59:21.656
by Luca Mazzarella from the European Institute of

1013
00:59:21.696 --> 00:59:22.836
Oncology in Milan.

1014
00:59:25.580 --> 00:59:27.320
So hi. Good afternoon, everybody.

1015
00:59:27.440 --> 00:59:29.760
Thanks a lot, Hugh, for the kind invitation.

1016
00:59:30.380 --> 00:59:31.060
So I'm going to

1017
00:59:32.000 --> 00:59:35.300
tell you about a story that we've developed over the years in the lab,

1018
00:59:35.460 --> 00:59:39.380
which we think led to a novel understanding of

1019
00:59:39.440 --> 00:59:40.080
an old

1020
00:59:41.360 --> 00:59:42.240
tumor suppressor,

1021
00:59:43.280 --> 00:59:46.760
which is of general interest across different tumors, as you will see.

1022
00:59:47.120 --> 00:59:50.120
So NF1, which takes its name from this

1023
00:59:51.120 --> 00:59:54.980
genetic disease called neurofibromatosis, which has at the same time predisposition

1024
00:59:55.060 --> 00:59:58.260
to cancer and neurodevelopmental defects,

1025
00:59:59.580 --> 01:00:03.480
was very early on identified to be caused by loss

1026
01:00:03.520 --> 01:00:07.220
of function mutations of this gene, which turned out to be one of the

1027
01:00:07.280 --> 01:00:10.820
earliest tumor suppressors ever cloned back in

1028
01:00:10.860 --> 01:00:14.760
1991 by Francis Collins. And very early on, it

1029
01:00:14.820 --> 01:00:18.660
was noticed that NF1 had structural homology with

1030
01:00:18.720 --> 01:00:22.540
a GTPase activating protein that had as their

1031
01:00:22.580 --> 01:00:23.580
target Ras.

1032
01:00:24.540 --> 01:00:28.240
And so it was discovered very early on that you

1033
01:00:28.300 --> 01:00:31.820
could isolate the GRD domain, the

1034
01:00:31.880 --> 01:00:33.200
GAP-related domain

1035
01:00:34.060 --> 01:00:37.720
of NF1. NF1 is a huge protein that

1036
01:00:37.860 --> 01:00:40.800
is very difficult to produce in recombinant fashion.

1037
01:00:41.180 --> 01:00:45.040
I always like to tell that if you want to make it into

1038
01:00:45.080 --> 01:00:48.660
bacteria, you have to so heavily optimize

1039
01:00:48.980 --> 01:00:52.900
the codons that the sequence eventually doesn't blast to the

1040
01:00:53.160 --> 01:00:56.840
original NF1 sequence anymore. But it was

1041
01:00:56.940 --> 01:01:00.040
easy and feasible to isolate the Ras

1042
01:01:00.580 --> 01:01:04.380
interacting domain. And therefore, for many, many years, I would

1043
01:01:04.460 --> 01:01:08.300
say the vast majority of the research on NF1 has been

1044
01:01:08.560 --> 01:01:12.080
carried out with the founding idea that NF1 acts as a

1045
01:01:12.240 --> 01:01:14.220
GTPase activating protein for Ras.

1046
01:01:14.320 --> 01:01:18.260
And therefore, the disease that comes from it is considered to be a Rasopathy, so a

1047
01:01:18.300 --> 01:01:21.140
disease where you have constitutive activation of Ras.

1048
01:01:21.660 --> 01:01:25.480
And also in cancer genomics, of course, everyone is used to

1049
01:01:25.520 --> 01:01:29.060
thinking of NF1 as an activator of

1050
01:01:29.340 --> 01:01:29.660
Ras.

1051
01:01:30.620 --> 01:01:33.760
And this comes from the recent papers that

1052
01:01:35.540 --> 01:01:39.340
revealed the structure of NF1. NF1 is a dimer

1053
01:01:40.040 --> 01:01:42.209
that has two main conformations,

1054
01:01:43.300 --> 01:01:46.830
closed or open, depending on the possibility to interact with Ras.

1055
01:01:46.890 --> 01:01:50.760
And as you can see in the model, basically, everything takes place at

1056
01:01:50.800 --> 01:01:54.260
the plasma membrane on this upper

1057
01:01:54.300 --> 01:01:58.260
convex face of NF1.

1058
01:01:58.780 --> 01:02:00.900
But hardly anything happens on this other side.

1059
01:02:01.480 --> 01:02:05.420
And so, one wonders what all this protein structure is there

1060
01:02:05.460 --> 01:02:09.240
to do if basically everything happens in these two small

1061
01:02:09.260 --> 01:02:09.780
domains.

1062
01:02:11.340 --> 01:02:15.140
So we got interested in NF1 because a few years ago, we were

1063
01:02:15.540 --> 01:02:19.310
looking at genes that are differentially mutated between metastatic and

1064
01:02:19.400 --> 01:02:22.600
primary breast cancer, and specifically in

1065
01:02:22.660 --> 01:02:26.200
HER2-positive breast cancer. By comparing different data sets, we

1066
01:02:26.260 --> 01:02:28.980
realized that NF1, together with P53,

1067
01:02:29.800 --> 01:02:30.040
is

1068
01:02:31.320 --> 01:02:35.200
one of the most differentially mutated genes in the genome.

1069
01:02:35.280 --> 01:02:39.030
So we got interested in this also because HER2-positive breast cancer, as you all

1070
01:02:39.100 --> 01:02:42.800
know, is almost invariably treated

1071
01:02:43.160 --> 01:02:46.660
also in the adjuvant setting with anti-HER2 therapies.

1072
01:02:47.070 --> 01:02:51.020
And therefore, the presence of something that is enriched in the metastatic setting

1073
01:02:51.080 --> 01:02:54.780
is most likely either due to a favoring of the

1074
01:02:54.820 --> 01:02:58.540
metastatic phenotype, but also possibly to resistance to different

1075
01:02:58.550 --> 01:03:02.310
therapies. This was the original idea, and that was the reason why

1076
01:03:02.740 --> 01:03:05.800
we decided to conduct-- We CRISPR knocked out

1077
01:03:06.580 --> 01:03:10.560
NF1 in several models, cell models, several models of HER2-positive breast

1078
01:03:10.640 --> 01:03:14.380
cancer. And we conducted a screen of different drugs, both

1079
01:03:14.420 --> 01:03:18.260
chemotherapy and targeted drugs that are normally used

1080
01:03:18.500 --> 01:03:22.460
in HER2-positive breast cancer. We were right in our hypothesis, which is

1081
01:03:22.520 --> 01:03:26.400
actually scooped while we were preparing the paper by a group in New

1082
01:03:26.460 --> 01:03:29.500
York. And so old school

1083
01:03:29.860 --> 01:03:32.240
HER2-targeting therapies

1084
01:03:32.860 --> 01:03:36.760
were certainly less

1085
01:03:36.800 --> 01:03:38.740
effective in the NF1 knockout cells.

1086
01:03:39.080 --> 01:03:40.750
But we were quite struck by

1087
01:03:41.860 --> 01:03:45.640
a totally serendipitous finding, which was that the

1088
01:03:45.660 --> 01:03:49.430
cells became instead more sensitive to T-DM1 antibody drug

1089
01:03:49.500 --> 01:03:51.360
conjugate that I'm sure you all know.

1090
01:03:51.380 --> 01:03:52.860
But just as a recap,

1091
01:03:53.880 --> 01:03:57.820
sorry, is a conjugation of trastuzumab that targets HER2

1092
01:03:57.840 --> 01:03:58.910
positive with a linker

1093
01:03:59.780 --> 01:04:03.580
that carries a payload which is DM1 that belongs to a class of drugs called the

1094
01:04:03.620 --> 01:04:06.200
maytansinoids that have a peculiarity.

1095
01:04:06.220 --> 01:04:09.760
They are microtubule binding drugs, and they are the only

1096
01:04:10.260 --> 01:04:14.040
microtubule binding drug where the binding site actually sits at the

1097
01:04:14.100 --> 01:04:18.060
interface between two alpha-beta heterodimers

1098
01:04:18.780 --> 01:04:21.040
that are incorporated in the microtubule.

1099
01:04:21.100 --> 01:04:22.840
And you will see that this is important for

1100
01:04:24.460 --> 01:04:26.280
the mechanism of action.

1101
01:04:27.420 --> 01:04:30.340
Is it? Yeah, sorry. I don't know why

1102
01:04:31.260 --> 01:04:34.980
the resolution is so bad. But so this is to show

1103
01:04:35.060 --> 01:04:36.260
that if you

1104
01:04:37.740 --> 01:04:40.310
look at the effect of the drug over time,

1105
01:04:41.300 --> 01:04:43.190
where some of the differences become more

1106
01:04:44.620 --> 01:04:48.440
obvious, and then you see that T-DM1, the gray

1107
01:04:48.900 --> 01:04:51.520
line, is the wild-type cell, and the knockout cell is in blue.

1108
01:04:51.840 --> 01:04:55.500
You see that there is a huge difference, this is on a log scale, in the

1109
01:04:55.560 --> 01:04:55.840
growth

1110
01:04:56.780 --> 01:04:59.460
curve in response to T-DM1 of these cells.

1111
01:04:59.700 --> 01:05:03.430
But then if you split the drug between trastuzumab and DM1, because we really

1112
01:05:03.500 --> 01:05:06.800
wanted to know whether this differential activity was due to the antibody part,

1113
01:05:07.220 --> 01:05:10.800
different incorporation of the drug, or other things that could be

1114
01:05:10.860 --> 01:05:13.120
attributed to the antibody or to the payload.

1115
01:05:13.760 --> 01:05:17.608
The payload was really able tophenocopy the treatment with

1116
01:05:17.928 --> 01:05:19.948
the whole antibody drug conjugate.

1117
01:05:21.008 --> 01:05:24.728
And so basically, and importantly, you do not

1118
01:05:24.788 --> 01:05:28.388
obtain the same differential with another antibody drug conjugate where the payload

1119
01:05:28.428 --> 01:05:31.608
is different and it's a topoisomerase inhibitor like TDXD.

1120
01:05:32.668 --> 01:05:36.408
We could demonstrate that this differential effect can also be elicited in

1121
01:05:36.448 --> 01:05:40.068
mice. We did experiments where we implanted in the two flanks of

1122
01:05:40.188 --> 01:05:42.258
NSG mice, wild type or knockout cells.

1123
01:05:42.588 --> 01:05:45.948
We treated the mice with the same dose of DM1, and you

1124
01:05:46.028 --> 01:05:49.228
see that very clearly, the knockout cells

1125
01:05:49.608 --> 01:05:52.288
responded much, much better to the same drug.

1126
01:05:52.628 --> 01:05:56.028
And also we could assemble a cohort of patients across the world.

1127
01:05:56.068 --> 01:06:00.028
It was a very difficult work. Eventually, we ended up

1128
01:06:00.088 --> 01:06:02.448
with 34 patients, for which

1129
01:06:03.288 --> 01:06:06.308
we had both treatment and genomics

1130
01:06:06.828 --> 01:06:10.628
informations. And there was clearly a difference, a statistically

1131
01:06:10.688 --> 01:06:14.448
significant difference in progression-free survival in the NF1 mutated

1132
01:06:14.528 --> 01:06:15.008
patients.

1133
01:06:16.248 --> 01:06:19.808
And importantly, if you then try to make the same

1134
01:06:19.848 --> 01:06:23.708
experiment with oncogenic RAS, so we expressed in the

1135
01:06:23.808 --> 01:06:26.028
same cells where we had knocked out NF1,

1136
01:06:26.968 --> 01:06:29.928
the oncogenic version of RAS, a

1137
01:06:29.968 --> 01:06:33.188
G12V mutation, you do not get any

1138
01:06:33.968 --> 01:06:35.808
differential sensitivity whatsoever.

1139
01:06:36.168 --> 01:06:40.108
So this was one of the first indications that this differential sensitivity

1140
01:06:40.168 --> 01:06:43.488
is at least not replicated by

1141
01:06:44.188 --> 01:06:45.628
RAS hyperactivation.

1142
01:06:46.748 --> 01:06:50.408
Another thing that we noticed was that these cells

1143
01:06:50.448 --> 01:06:54.248
exhibit a mitotic defect. So if you look at the length of

1144
01:06:54.268 --> 01:06:58.188
mitosis in the knockout cells, you can clearly appreciate that the length is

1145
01:06:58.548 --> 01:07:02.368
significantly longer, and you can appreciate a number of mitotic

1146
01:07:02.428 --> 01:07:05.808
abnormalities like lagging chromatids, that

1147
01:07:05.888 --> 01:07:09.808
eventually result in a statistically significant difference

1148
01:07:09.888 --> 01:07:13.098
in the fraction of cells with misaligned chromosomes,

1149
01:07:13.748 --> 01:07:17.528
which importantly is entirely rescued when you re-express

1150
01:07:17.688 --> 01:07:21.008
the wild-type version of NF1. And this

1151
01:07:21.068 --> 01:07:25.027
importantly, can also be seen in patients, because if you look

1152
01:07:25.048 --> 01:07:26.368
at the Gini data and you

1153
01:07:27.388 --> 01:07:31.108
calculate the aneuploidy score, you see the NF1 mutants

1154
01:07:31.168 --> 01:07:33.708
tend to have a higher aneuploidy score.

1155
01:07:33.748 --> 01:07:35.328
I don't know what's wrong with the slides, but

1156
01:07:36.728 --> 01:07:38.328
they were fine on my computer, so

1157
01:07:39.168 --> 01:07:39.908
sorry about that.

1158
01:07:40.808 --> 01:07:41.308
But so

1159
01:07:42.388 --> 01:07:44.648
what does NF1 have to do with microtubules?

1160
01:07:44.708 --> 01:07:46.728
Because there was no strong evidence,

1161
01:07:47.848 --> 01:07:50.228
definitely it's not dependent on RAS.

1162
01:07:50.728 --> 01:07:51.388
And the

1163
01:07:52.288 --> 01:07:56.028
connection between NF1 and microtubules has been sort

1164
01:07:56.068 --> 01:08:00.008
of lingering in the literature for many, many years because this was actually

1165
01:08:00.268 --> 01:08:04.128
one of the earliest findings. If you try to purify NF1

1166
01:08:04.168 --> 01:08:08.108
from insect cells, tubulin co-precipitates with neurofibromin, but it

1167
01:08:08.148 --> 01:08:09.928
was never really followed up very much.

1168
01:08:10.148 --> 01:08:12.928
So we decided to investigate a little bit more on this.

1169
01:08:12.968 --> 01:08:16.768
And first of all, one of the things that we did was to look at the

1170
01:08:17.548 --> 01:08:19.208
intracellular localization of NF1,

1171
01:08:20.288 --> 01:08:23.468
because as I mentioned before, the existing model

1172
01:08:23.989 --> 01:08:27.928
postulates that basically everything happens at the cell membrane for the

1173
01:08:27.949 --> 01:08:31.888
interaction with RAS. But in fact, we did not find any strong evidence

1174
01:08:31.989 --> 01:08:35.708
of NF1 localization in the plasma membrane or in any other membrane.

1175
01:08:35.757 --> 01:08:39.248
Instead, we did find a localization on the mitotic

1176
01:08:39.329 --> 01:08:42.768
spindle, and which was also confirmed by proximity

1177
01:08:42.808 --> 01:08:44.449
localization assay.

1178
01:08:45.508 --> 01:08:47.268
And then if you try to

1179
01:08:48.248 --> 01:08:52.108
look at the interaction in vitro, then this becomes very, very evident, because if

1180
01:08:52.148 --> 01:08:55.468
you purify NF1 and you co-sediment it with

1181
01:08:55.688 --> 01:08:58.628
microtubules, it actually precipitates together with

1182
01:08:59.329 --> 01:09:03.088
polymerized microtubules, as you see in the co-sedimentation assay on the

1183
01:09:03.128 --> 01:09:06.638
left. And also, if you visualize the interaction by

1184
01:09:06.869 --> 01:09:10.468
negative staining and electron microscopy, you can see a very nicely

1185
01:09:10.508 --> 01:09:14.128
decorated microtubule in the

1186
01:09:14.148 --> 01:09:18.108
images on the right. And so NF1, it doesn't simply stick to

1187
01:09:18.148 --> 01:09:19.369
the microtubules. It actually

1188
01:09:21.348 --> 01:09:24.329
alters the polymerization dynamics of tubulin.

1189
01:09:24.409 --> 01:09:28.168
So we did this old-fashioned tubulin polymerization assay where all you

1190
01:09:28.208 --> 01:09:28.848
measure is the

1191
01:09:29.888 --> 01:09:33.409
turbidity of the solution where tubulin is polymerizing in

1192
01:09:33.468 --> 01:09:34.338
microtubules, and this

1193
01:09:35.188 --> 01:09:39.128
normally follows a sigmoidal shape over time, where at the beginning you have a

1194
01:09:39.168 --> 01:09:43.068
lagging phase with nucleation of early microtubules, then a linear

1195
01:09:43.108 --> 01:09:46.708
phase where the microtubules start growing very fast, and then a steady

1196
01:09:46.848 --> 01:09:50.188
state where the rate of incorporation and elimination is

1197
01:09:50.748 --> 01:09:51.068
fixed.

1198
01:09:52.068 --> 01:09:55.048
And what we could see was that this is the standard

1199
01:09:55.588 --> 01:09:59.028
sigmoidal curve that you see for normal tubulin polymerization.

1200
01:09:59.438 --> 01:10:03.288
The addition of the maytansinoid drug, as you can see, completely abrogated

1201
01:10:03.388 --> 01:10:07.308
any polymerization. But then you see that when you add

1202
01:10:07.348 --> 01:10:11.158
recombinant NF1 in the solution, the whole curve is massively

1203
01:10:11.208 --> 01:10:15.168
shifted to the left. And also the addition of DM1, it

1204
01:10:15.228 --> 01:10:17.027
doesn't really make any difference.

1205
01:10:17.188 --> 01:10:21.028
So it's actually in a reductionist system where there's

1206
01:10:21.108 --> 01:10:25.088
no additional protein, there's no RAS or anything else, NF1 is

1207
01:10:25.148 --> 01:10:29.008
directly able to accelerate polymerization of tubulin and

1208
01:10:29.168 --> 01:10:31.528
to counteract the activity of the drug.

1209
01:10:32.308 --> 01:10:36.128
We looked even more carefully at that in these in vitro assays where you

1210
01:10:36.188 --> 01:10:39.788
can make seeds of microtubules that you can see here in

1211
01:10:40.028 --> 01:10:43.868
magenta. They are stabilized by taxol, and then you add in the solution

1212
01:10:44.348 --> 01:10:47.928
green fluorescent tubulin that is used to visualize

1213
01:10:48.328 --> 01:10:51.988
the growth and shrinkage, the so-called dynamic instability of the

1214
01:10:52.068 --> 01:10:55.768
microtubules. And you can clearly see that in the presence of NF1,

1215
01:10:56.168 --> 01:11:00.088
the microtubules are way more dynamic and the growth rate is accelerated.

1216
01:11:00.508 --> 01:11:04.088
But also when you treat with the drugs, you see on the left that the

1217
01:11:04.148 --> 01:11:08.128
addition of DM1 basically almost completely abolishes any growth.

1218
01:11:08.868 --> 01:11:12.708
But as you start adding NF1, the more you add, the more you

1219
01:11:12.748 --> 01:11:15.768
counteract this activity, and the microtubules are able to grow

1220
01:11:16.188 --> 01:11:19.988
despite the presence of DM1.And you can also

1221
01:11:20.068 --> 01:11:23.988
show the same thing in vivo because you can transfect the cells with a

1222
01:11:24.028 --> 01:11:26.448
reporter that produces a

1223
01:11:27.268 --> 01:11:28.908
fluorescent protein, the EB3

1224
01:11:30.228 --> 01:11:31.528
GFP bound, that

1225
01:11:32.448 --> 01:11:36.248
binds to the tips of the microtubules, and so you are able

1226
